Introduction

Hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection is the most common bloodborne infection in the United States. In addition to this, national incidence rates for the disease have nearly doubled in the last decade. While the âbaby-boomerâ generation (those born between 1946 and 1964, and most likely to have received a blood transfusion before universal screening guidelines) has historically been identified as a key at-risk population, an increasing number of new cases have been reported in younger individuals.

In this assignment, I will visualize trends in HCV incidence rate for the age groups included in the dataset, and determine which group has had the steepest or most dramatic increase in new cases for the period of interest.

This dataset has 6 variables: âIndicatorâ (âAcute Viral Hepatitis Câ for all observations), âYearâ, âAge.Group,â Casesâ, âRate.per.100.000â and âXâ (denotes the type of rate, âIncidence Rateâ across all observations).

Methods

My chosen dataset comes from the CDCâs National Center for HIV, Viral Hepatitis, STD, and Tuberculosis Prevention (NCHHSTP) site. This centerâs site provides access to AtlasPlus, an interactive tool that allows users, like myself, to download disease surveillance data from the last 20 years. Using this tool, I downloaded national age-specific incidence rates for Hepatitis C (HCV) from 2000 to 2022.

In cleaning the data, I chose to first remove the âIndicatorâ and âXâ columns, as they were consistent across all observations. I also made sure to check for missing values, although collecting data through AtlasPlus should have not included any of this type of data. Further, I renamed the remaining variables to be more concise and consistent. Finally, I gathered measures of central tendency and spread for my continous variables using the summary() function.

# Remove "Indicator" and "X" Columns
library(dplyr)

data <- data %>%
  select(-Indicator, -X)

# Check for Missing Data
missing_data <- colSums(is.na(data))
missing_data
            Year        Age.Group            Cases Rate.per.100.000 
               0                0                0                0 
# Rename Variables
data <- data |>
  rename(
    year = Year,
    age_group = Age.Group,
    cases = Cases,
    incidence_rate = Rate.per.100.000)

# Variable Summaries

Number of Observations per Year

year_summary <- data |>
  group_by(year) |>
  summarise(observations = n())

colnames(year_summary) <- c("Year", "Number of Observations")

Average Yearly Incidence per 100,000 (All Age Groups)

average_yearly_incidence <- data |>
  group_by(year) |>
  summarise(
    average_rate = mean(incidence_rate, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_rate = sd(incidence_rate, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop")

colnames(average_yearly_incidence) <- c("Year", "Average Incidence Rate", "Standard Deviation")

Average Incidence per 100,000 by Age Group (All Years)

average_group_incidence <- data |>
  group_by(age_group) |>
  summarise(
    average_group = mean(incidence_rate, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_group = sd(incidence_rate, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop")

colnames(average_group_incidence) <- c("Age Group", "Average Incidence Rate", "Standard Deviation")

Lineplot of Yearly Incidence Rates per 100,000 by Age Groups

ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = year, y = incidence_rate, color = age_group, group = age_group)) +
  labs(title = "Yearly Incidence Rates per 100,000 by Age Groups",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Incidence Rate per 100,000",
       color = "Age Group") +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "RdPu") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
